        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "I think `nvim_buf_set_extmark` has the same issue, where inccommand highlights end up with a lower priority. I've been hitting an issue for a while with `mini.indentscope`, where the scope renders above the inccommand highlights. When substituting the current line with `:s:.*:new contents of line`, it renders as:\r\n<img width=\"348\" height=\"99\" alt=\"image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/f1512390-9c34-4be4-a2d1-00bb388ccd86\" />\r\n\r\nTaking a look under the hood, `mini.indentscope` uses `nvim_buf_set_extmark` to render the current scope:\r\n```lua\r\nH.make_draw_function = function(indicator, opts)\r\n  local extmark_opts = {\r\n    hl_mode = 'combine',\r\n    priority = opts.priority,\r\n    right_gravity = false,\r\n    virt_text = indicator.virt_text,\r\n    virt_text_win_col = indicator.virt_text_win_col,\r\n    virt_text_pos = 'overlay',\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  if H.has_wrapped_virt_text and vim.wo.breakindent and vim.wo.showbreak == '' then\r\n    extmark_opts.virt_text_repeat_linebreak = true\r\n  end\r\n\r\n  local current_event_id = opts.event_id\r\n\r\n  return function(l)\r\n    -- Don't draw if outdated\r\n    if H.current.event_id ~= current_event_id and current_event_id ~= nil then return false end\r\n\r\n    -- Don't draw if disabled\r\n    if H.is_disabled() then return false end\r\n\r\n    -- Don't put extmark outside of indicator range\r\n    if not (indicator.top <= l and l <= indicator.bottom) then return true end\r\n\r\n    return pcall(vim.api.nvim_buf_set_extmark, indicator.buf_id, H.ns_id, l - 1, 0, extmark_opts)\r\n  end\r\nend\r\n```\r\n\r\nI've found that no matter what priority I use here, it always renders above the inccommand highlight. i don't want to bikeshed this PR, so I can make a separate issue if that's preferred - I moreso wanted to see if I'm on the right track as to what the problem is.",
